President Biden has appointed members to the Committee for the Preservation of the White House, an advisory committee responsible for preserving the White House and its collections. The committee is composed of citizens with expertise in historic preservation, architecture, decorative arts, and scholarship in these areas. It establishes policies for the museum function of the White House, makes recommendations on acquisitions for its permanent collection, and advises on changes to principal rooms and guest suites. The First Lady serves as Honorary Chair, and the Director of the National Park Service serves as Chair. Other members include the Curator of the White House, Chief Usher of the White House, Secretary of the Smithsonian Institution, Chair of the United States Commission of Fine Arts, and Director of the National Gallery of Art. The appointed individuals include photographers, museum curators, furniture curators, disability rights advocates, horticulturists, and cultural ambassadors, among others.